it does not imply that the CO2 effect becomes saturated at high concentrations. In fact, the paper notes that \\\"the incremental increase in temperature resulting from further increases in CO2 concentration would decrease,\\\" which is opposite of what saturation would imply. Additionally, numerous other studies have confirmed that the CO2 effect remains strong even at high concentrations, based on observations and computer simulations. For example, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Fourth Assessment Report states that \\\"the current understanding of the relationship between atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases and global mean surface temperature is based on a large body of empirical evidence, and much of this evidence comes from observations and modeling experiments that were conducted over the past few decades.\\\"\"\n"label: true
